value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways involving box H/ACA type small nucleolar RNA.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lipid stimulus.
Catalysis of the removal of 8-oxo-7,8-dihydroguanine bases by cleaving the N-C1' glycosidic bond between the oxidized purine and the deoxyribose sugar.

Catalysis of the reaction: deoxynucleoside triphosphate + DNA(n) = diphosphate + DNA(n+1); the synthesis of DNA from deoxyribonucleotide triphosphates in the presence of a nucleic acid template and a 3'hydroxyl group.

Catalysis of the reaction: nucleoside triphosphate + RNA(n) = diphosphate + RNA(n+1); the synthesis of RNA from ribonucleotide triphosphates in the presence of a nucleic acid template, via extension of the 3'-end.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and RNA molecules to form a stress granule.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the Golgi apparatus.

The formation of chromatin containing the histone H3 variant CENP-A to form centromeric chromatin. This specialised chromatin occurs at centromeric region in point centromeres, and the central core in modular centromeres.
The process in which the sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome become associated with each other during S phase.

The process in which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained as chromosomes condense, attach to the spindle in a bipolar orientation, and congress to the metaphase plate.

label.value: establishment of mitotic sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: The process in which the sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome become joined along the entire length of the chromosome during S phase during a mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: maintenance of mitotic sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: The process in which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained as chromosomes condense, attach to the spindle in a bipolar orientation, and congress to the metaphase plate during a mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: regulation of maintenance of sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: Any process that modulates the extent to which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained.

label.value: negative regulation of maintenance of sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: Any process that decreases the extent to which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained.

label.value: positive regulation of maintenance of sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: Any process that increases the extent to which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained.

label.value: regulation of maintenance of mitotic sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: Any process that modulates the extent to which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained during a mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: negative regulation of maintenance of mitotic sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: Any process that decreases the extent to which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained during a mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: positive regulation of maintenance of mitotic sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: Any process that increases the extent to which the association between sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome is maintained during a mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: cellular response to amino acid starvation

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of amino acids.
Catalysis of the acetylation of an amino acid residue of a peptide or protein, according to the reaction: acetyl-CoA + peptide = CoA + N-acetylpeptide.
The process in which a carbohydrate is transported across a membrane.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: A process in which a monoatomic ion is transported across a membrane. Monatomic ions (also called simple ions) are ions consisting of exactly one atom.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

label.value: cellular response to zinc ion starvation

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of zinc ions.
The addition a sulfur atom to a nucleotide in a tRNA molecule.

label.value: regulation of transcription elongation by RNA polymerase II

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transcription elongation, the extension of an RNA molecule after transcription initiation and promoter clearance by the addition of ribonucleotides, catalyzed by RNA polymerase II.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription elongation by RNA polymerase II

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription elongation, the extension of an RNA molecule after transcription initiation and promoter clearance by the addition of ribonucleotides, catalyzed by RNA polymerase II.

A DNA-directed RNA polymerase complex located in the mitochondrion. Mitochondrial RNA polymerase is composed of two subunits, a catalytic core, which resembles the enzymes from bacteriophage T7 and T3, and a specificity factor required for promoter recognition, which is similar to members of the eubacterial sigma factor family. In S. cerevisiae, these are encoded by the nuclear genes RPO41 and MTF1 and the specificity factor, required for promoter recognition and initiation, is not present in the elongating form.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving amides.

label.value: negative regulation of amide metabolic process

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving amides.

label.value: positive regulation of amide metabolic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving amides.
Any process that stops or reduces the rate of GTP hydrolysis by a GTPase.

definition.value: An example of this is P2xA in Dictyostelium (UniProt symbol Q86JM7) in PMID:24335649.

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a monosaccharide stimulus.
The formation of spores derived from the products of meiosis.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of spore formation from the products of meiosis. An example of this is found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of ascospore formation. An example of this process is found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

The actin nucleation process in which actin monomers combine to form a new branch on the side of an existing actin filament; mediated by the Arp2/3 protein complex and its interaction with other proteins.

label.value: regulation of Arp2/3 complex-mediated actin nucleation

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of actin nucleation mediated by the Arp2/3 complex and interacting proteins.

label.value: negative regulation of Arp2/3 complex-mediated actin nucleation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of actin nucleation mediated by the Arp2/3 complex and interacting proteins.
The process of assisting in the covalent and noncovalent assembly of single or multimeric RNAs into the correct tertiary structure.
Catalysis of the removal of a 5' terminal diphosphate from the 5'-triphosphate end of an mRNA, leaving a 5'-monophosphate end.
A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a lipid particle.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the external part of the cell wall and/or plasma membrane.
Any process in which a telomere is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.
The process in which a telomere is maintained in a specific location at the nuclear periphery.
The portion of the nuclear lumen proximal to the inner nuclear membrane.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of the mRNA transcript body that occurs when the 5' end is not protected by a 5'-cap; degradation proceeds in the 5' to 3' direction.
Catalysis of the reaction: P1-P6-bis(5'-adenosyl) hexaphosphate + H2O = AMP + adenosine 5'-pentaphosphate.
Any process in which a microtubule is maintained in a specific location in a cell.
Unwinding of an RNA helix in the 3' to 5' direction, driven by ATP hydrolysis.

The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and RNA molecules to form a 90S preribosome. The 90S preribosome represents the complex that forms on the primary rRNA transcript before it splits into the small subunit and large subunit portions.
